etymologies: early 17th century. From Island Massachusett sanomp, sanop (pronounced/saːnʌ̃p/), cognate with Eastern Abenaki sénαpe man from an Algonquian base of uncertain sense and origin + the Algonquian base of Unami Delaware -á:p:e person

definitions: Among some North American Indian peoples of New England: a man of a social class below that of a chief; a man under the authority of a chief.
